outcomes.title: Geometric Optimization
outcomes.description: Sketch the feasible region of a linear optimization problem and identify the optimal solution geomtrically.
outcomes.template:
Consider the following linear optimization problem:

\begin{array}{rl} \text{Maximize }f(x,y) & = {{f}}\\ \text{Subject to:} & \\ {{A1}} & \leq {{b1}}\\ {{A2}} & \leq {{b2}}\\ {{A3}} & \leq {{b3}}\\ x,y & \geq 0. \end{array}

Sketch the feasible region, then find the point on the feasible region which maximizes f(x,y) = {{f}}. After which plot the objective line through this point, along with an arrow orthogonal to this line which increases the objective function.

f is maximized at {{point}} with f{{point}}={{soln}}.

outcomes.title: Simplex Pivots
outcomes.description: Identify valid pivot positions in a tableau and be able to perform a simplex pivot.
outcomes.template:
Consider the linear optimization problem encoded by the following tableau:

\begin{array}{|ccccc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & {{x4}} & {{x5}} & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{a15}} & {{b1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{a25}} & {{b2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} & {{a35}} & {{b3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}} & {{a45}} & {{b4}} & = -{{t4}}\\ {{a51}} & {{a52}} & {{a53}} & {{a54}} & {{a55}} & {{b5}} & = -{{t5}}\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{c4}} & {{c5}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

Identify the valid pivots according to the simplex algorithm. Then pick one and perform it.

The valid pivots are on entries a_{ {{pv1i}} {{pv1j}} }, a_{ {{pv2i}} {{pv2j}} } and a_{ {{pv3i}} {{pv3j}} }.

Pivoting on a_{ {{pv1i}} {{pv1j}} } produces: \begin{array}{|ccccc|c|l} {{p1x1}} & {{p1x2}} & {{p1x3}} & {{p1x4}} & {{p1x5}} & -1\\ \hline {{p1a11}} & {{p1a12}} & {{p1a13}} & {{p1a14}} & {{p1a15}} & {{p1b1}} & = -{{p1t1}}\\ {{p1a21}} & {{p1a22}} & {{p1a23}} & {{p1a24}} & {{p1a25}} & {{p1b2}} & = -{{p1t2}}\\ {{p1a31}} & {{p1a32}} & {{p1a33}} & {{p1a34}} & {{p1a35}} & {{p1b3}} & = -{{p1t3}}\\ {{p1a41}} & {{p1a42}} & {{p1a43}} & {{p1a44}} & {{p1a45}} & {{p1b4}} & = -{{p1t4}}\\ {{p1a51}} & {{p1a52}} & {{p1a53}} & {{p1a54}} & {{p1a55}} & {{p1b5}} & = -{{p1t5}}\\ \hline {{p1c1}} & {{p1c2}} & {{p1c3}} & {{p1c4}} & {{p1c5}} & {{p1d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

Pivoting on a_{ {{pv2i}} {{pv2j}} } produces: \begin{array}{|ccccc|c|l} {{p2x1}} & {{p2x2}} & {{p2x3}} & {{p2x4}} & {{p2x5}} & -1\\ \hline {{p2a11}} & {{p2a12}} & {{p2a13}} & {{p2a14}} & {{p2a15}} & {{p2b1}} & = -{{p2t1}}\\ {{p2a21}} & {{p2a22}} & {{p2a23}} & {{p2a24}} & {{p2a25}} & {{p2b2}} & = -{{p2t2}}\\ {{p2a31}} & {{p2a32}} & {{p2a33}} & {{p2a34}} & {{p2a35}} & {{p2b3}} & = -{{p2t3}}\\ {{p2a41}} & {{p2a42}} & {{p2a43}} & {{p2a44}} & {{p2a45}} & {{p2b4}} & = -{{p2t4}}\\ {{p2a51}} & {{p2a52}} & {{p2a53}} & {{p2a54}} & {{p2a55}} & {{p2b5}} & = -{{p2t5}}\\ \hline {{p2c1}} & {{p2c2}} & {{p2c3}} & {{p2c4}} & {{p2c5}} & {{p2d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

Pivoting on a_{ {{pv3i}} {{pv3j}} } produces: \begin{array}{|ccccc|c|l} {{p3x1}} & {{p3x2}} & {{p3x3}} & {{p3x4}} & {{p3x5}} & -1\\ \hline {{p3a11}} & {{p3a12}} & {{p3a13}} & {{p3a14}} & {{p3a15}} & {{p3b1}} & = -{{p3t1}}\\ {{p3a21}} & {{p3a22}} & {{p3a23}} & {{p3a24}} & {{p3a25}} & {{p3b2}} & = -{{p3t2}}\\ {{p3a31}} & {{p3a32}} & {{p3a33}} & {{p3a34}} & {{p3a35}} & {{p3b3}} & = -{{p3t3}}\\ {{p3a41}} & {{p3a42}} & {{p3a43}} & {{p3a44}} & {{p3a45}} & {{p3b4}} & = -{{p3t4}}\\ {{p3a51}} & {{p3a52}} & {{p3a53}} & {{p3a54}} & {{p3a55}} & {{p3b5}} & = -{{p3t5}}\\ \hline {{p3c1}} & {{p3c2}} & {{p3c3}} & {{p3c4}} & {{p3c5}} & {{p3d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

outcomes.title: Simplex Algorithm for Feasible Canonical Problems
outcomes.description: Find the optimal solution for feasible canonical problem.
outcomes.template:
Suppose we wish to maximize f(x_1, x_2, x_3, x_4) = {{objectivefunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{row1}} & \leq & {{b1}} \\ {{row2}} & \leq & {{b2}} \\ {{row3}} & \leq & {{b3}} \\ {{row4}} & \leq & {{b4}} \\ x_1, x_2, x_3, x_4 & \geq & 0. \end{array}

Encode this problem in a tableau and use the simplex algorithm to find the optimal solution.

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{|cccc|c|l} x_1 & x_2 & x_3 & x_4 & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{b1}} & = -t_1\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{b2}} & = -t_2\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} & {{b3}} & = -t_3\\ {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}} & {{b4}} & = -t_4\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{c4}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{|cccc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & {{x4}} & -1\\ \hline {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fa13}} & {{Fa14}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fa23}} & {{Fa24}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{Fa31}} & {{Fa32}} & {{Fa33}} & {{Fa34}} & {{Fb3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ {{Fa41}} & {{Fa42}} & {{Fa43}} & {{Fa44}} & {{Fb4}} & = -{{t4}}\\ \hline {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fc3}} & {{Fc4}} & {{Fd}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array} with x_1 = {{x1value}}, x_2 = {{x2value}}, x_3 = {{x3value}}, and x_4 = {{x4value}}. The optimal objective value is f({{x1value}}, {{x2value}}, {{x3value}}, {{x4value}}) = {{optimalsolution}}

outcomes.title: Unboundedness
outcomes.description: Determine when a tableau indicates either an unbounded feasible region and/or unbounded objective function.
outcomes.template:
For each of the following tableau, determine if the tableau currently indicates an unbounded feasible region, and if it indicates an unbounded objective function.

\begin{array}{|ccccc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & {{x4}} & {{x5}} & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{a15}} & {{b1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{a25}} & {{b2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} & {{a35}} & {{b3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}} & {{a45}} & {{b4}} & = -{{t4}}\\ {{a51}} & {{a52}} & {{a53}} & {{a54}} & {{a55}} & {{b5}} & = -{{t5}}\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{c4}} & {{c5}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

This tableau does does not indicate the linear optimization problem has an unbounded feasible region.

This tableau does does not indicate the linear optimization problem has an unbounded objective function.

outcomes.title: Simplex Algorithm for Unbounded Problems
outcomes.description: Identify when the objective function for a linear optimization problem with unbounded feasible region still has an optimal solution.
outcomes.template:
For each of the following tableau, use the simplex algorithm to determine if the given linear optimization problem achieves optimality, or if the objective function is unbounded.

Maximize f(x_1, x_2, x_3) = {{objectivefunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{row1}} & \leq & {{b1}} \\ {{row2}} & \leq & {{b2}} \\ {{row3}} & \leq & {{b3}} \\ x_1, x_2, x_3 & \geq & 0. \end{array}

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{|ccc|c|l} x_1 & x_2 & x_3 & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{b1}} & = -t_1\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{b2}} & = -t_2\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{b3}} & = -t_3\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{|ccc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & -1\\ \hline {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fa13}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fa23}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{Fa31}} & {{Fa32}} & {{Fa33}} & {{Fb3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ \hline {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fc3}} &{{Fd}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The objective function is unbounded (above). The optimal solution occurs when x_1 = {{x1value}}, x_2 = {{x2value}}, and x_3 = {{x3value}}. The optimal objective value is f({{x1value}}, {{x2value}}, {{x3value}}) = {{optimalsolution}}.

outcomes.title: Feasibility
outcomes.description: Determine when a tableau indicates either an unbounded feasible region and/or unbounded objective function.
outcomes.template:
For each of the following tableau, determine if the tableau currently indicates an infeasible basic solution, and if it indicates an infeasible feasible region.

\begin{array}{|ccccc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & {{x4}} & {{x5}} & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{a15}} & {{b1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{a25}} & {{b2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} & {{a35}} & {{b3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}} & {{a45}} & {{b4}} & = -{{t4}}\\ {{a51}} & {{a52}} & {{a53}} & {{a54}} & {{a55}} & {{b5}} & = -{{t5}}\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{c4}} & {{c5}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

This tableau does does not indicate that the basic solution is infeasible.

This tableau does does not indicate the linear optimization problem has an empty feasible region.

outcomes.title: Simplex Algorithm for Infeasible Problems
outcomes.description: Determine via the simplex algorithm whether a problem with infeasible basic solution has an empty feasible region or not.
outcomes.template:
For each of the following tableau, use the simplex algorithm to determine if the given linear optimization problem has an empty feasible region or not.

Maximize f(x_1, x_2, x_3) = {{objectivefunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{row1}} & \leq & {{b1}} \\ {{row2}} & \leq & {{b2}} \\ {{row3}} & \leq & {{b3}} \\ x_1, x_2, x_3 & \geq & 0. \end{array}

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{|ccc|c|l} x_1 & x_2 & x_3 & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{b1}} & = -t_1\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{b2}} & = -t_2\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{b3}} & = -t_3\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{|ccc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & -1\\ \hline {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fa13}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fa23}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{Fa31}} & {{Fa32}} & {{Fa33}} & {{Fb3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ \hline {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fc3}} &{{Fd}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The feasible region is empty. The feasible region is not empty and we may proceed with the simplex algorithm as usual.

outcomes.title: Solving Linear Optimization Problems
outcomes.description: Given a linear optimization problem, either solve it or determine if it is infeasible or unbounded.
outcomes.template:
For each of the following linear optimization problems, use the simplex algorithm to determine if the given linear optimization problem achieves optimality, or if the problem is infeasible or unbounded.

Maximize f(x_1, x_2, x_3) = {{objectivefunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{row1}} & \leq & {{b1}} \\ {{row2}} & \leq & {{b2}} \\ {{row3}} & \leq & {{b3}} \\ x_1, x_2, x_3 & \geq & 0. \end{array}

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{|ccc|c|l} x_1 & x_2 & x_3 & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{b1}} & = -t_1\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{b2}} & = -t_2\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{b3}} & = -t_3\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{|ccc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & -1\\ \hline {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fa13}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fa23}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{Fa31}} & {{Fa32}} & {{Fa33}} & {{Fb3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ \hline {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fc3}} &{{Fd}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The objective function is unbounded (above). The optimal solution occurs when x_1 = {{x1value}}, x_2 = {{x2value}}, and x_3 = {{x3value}}. The optimal objective value is f({{x1value}}, {{x2value}}, {{x3value}}) = {{optimalsolution}}. The feasible region is empty.

outcomes.title: Unconstrained Variables
outcomes.description: Convert a noncanonical linear optimization problem with unconstrained variables into a canonical problem.
outcomes.template:
Suppose we wish to maximize f(x_1, x_2) = {{objectivefunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{row1}} & \leq & {{b1}} \\ {{row2}} & \leq & {{b2}} \\ {{row3}} & \leq & {{b3}} \\ {{row4}} & \leq & {{b4}} \\ \end{array}

Encode this noncanonical problem in a tableau and use pivots to convert the problem into a canonical problem.

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{|cc|c|l} x_1 & x_2 & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{b1}} & = -t_1\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{b2}} & = -t_2\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{b3}} & = -t_3\\ {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{b4}} & = -t_4\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{|cc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & -1\\ \hline {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ \hline {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fd}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array} This is a feasible canonical problem and we may proceed as usual.

outcomes.title: Equality Constraints
outcomes.description: Convert a noncanonical linear optimization problem with equality constraints into a canonical problem.
outcomes.template:
Suppose we wish to maximize f(x_1, x_2) = {{objectivefunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{row1}} & = & {{b1}} \\ {{row2}} & = & {{b2}} \\ x_1, x_2, x_3, x_4 & \geq & 0 \\ \end{array}

Encode this noncanonical problem in a tableau and use pivots to convert the problem into a canonical problem.

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{|cccc|c|l} x_1 & x_2 & x_3 & x_4 & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{b1}} & = 0\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{b2}} & = 0\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{c4}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{|cc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & -1\\ \hline {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ \hline {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fd}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array} This is a feasible canonical problem and we may proceed as usual.

outcomes.title: Noncanonical Problems
outcomes.description: Solve a noncanonical linear optimization problem.
outcomes.template:
Suppose we wish to maximize f(x_1, x_2, x_3, x_4) = {{objectivefunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{row1}} & \leq & {{b1}} \\ {{row2}} & \leq & {{b2}} \\ {{row3}} & \leq & {{b3}} \\ {{row4}} & = & {{b4}} \\ x_1, x_2, x_3 & \geq & 0. \end{array}

Encode this noncanonical problem in a tableau and use pivots to convert the problem into a canonical problem, then solve it.

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{|cccc|c|l} x_1 & x_2 & x_3 & x_4 & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{b1}} & = -t_1\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{b2}} & = -t_2\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} & {{b3}} & = -t_3\\ {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}} & {{b4}} & = 0\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{c4}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{|ccc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & -1\\ \hline {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fa13}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fa23}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{Fa31}} & {{Fa32}} & {{Fa33}} & {{Fb3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ \hline {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fc3}} & {{Fd}}& =f\\ \hline \end{array} with x_1 = {{x1value}}, x_2 = {{x2value}}, x_3 = {{x3value}}, and x_4 = {{x4value}}. The optimal objective value is f({{x1value}}, {{x2value}}, {{x3value}}, {{x4value}}) = {{optimalsolution}}

outcomes.title: Sensitivity Analysis
outcomes.description: Find the change in the optimal solution of an objective function corresponding to changes in constraints.
outcomes.template:
Suppose that {{product1}} sells for ${{c1}} a unit and requires {{a11}} units of {{material1}}, {{a21}} units of {{material2}}, {{a31}} units of {{material3}}, and {{a41}} units of {{material4}}. {{product2}} sells for ${{c2}} a unit and requires {{a12}} units of {{material1}}, {{a22}} units of {{material2}}, {{a32}} units of {{material3}}, and {{a42}} units of {{material4}}. {{product3}} sells for ${{c3}} a unit and requires {{a13}} units of {{material1}}, {{a23}} units of {{material2}}, {{a33}} units of {{material3}}, and {{a43}} units of {{material4}}. {{product4}} sells for ${{c4}} a unit and requires {{a14}} units of {{material1}}, {{a24}} units of {{material2}}, {{a34}} units of {{material3}}, and {{a44}} units of {{material4}}. There are {{b1}} units of {{material1}}, {{b2}} units of {{material2}}, {{b3}} units of {{material3}}, {{b4}} units of {{material4}}. We wish to maximize revenue. For each material, if one were to recieve one more unit of each material, how would that change the optimal revenue?

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{|cccc|c|l} x_1 & x_2 & x_3 & x_4 & -1\\ \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{b1}} & = -t_1\\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{b2}} & = -t_2\\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} & {{b3}} & = -t_3\\ {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}} & {{b4}} & = -t_4\\ \hline {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{c4}} & {{d}}\\ \hline \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{|cccc|c|l} {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & {{x4}} & -1\\ \hline {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fa13}} & {{Fa14}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fa23}} & {{Fa24}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{Fa31}} & {{Fa32}} & {{Fa33}} & {{Fa34}} & {{Fb3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ {{Fa41}} & {{Fa42}} & {{Fa43}} & {{Fa44}} & {{Fb4}} & = -{{t4}}\\ \hline {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fc3}} & {{Fc4}} & {{Fd}}\\ \hline \end{array} Increasing the quantity of {{material1}} by one unit would increase the maximum revenue by {{y1value}} dollars. Increasing the quantity of {{material2}} by one unit would increase the maximum revenue by {{y2value}} dollars. Increasing the quantity of {{material3}} by one unit would increase the maximum revenue by {{y3value}} dollars. Increasing the quantity of {{material4}} by one unit would increase the maximum revenue by {{y4value}} dollars.

outcomes.title: Dual Tableau
outcomes.description: Determine when a tableau indicates, infeasibility, unboundedness or optimality for the dual problem.
outcomes.template:
For each of the following tableau, determine if the tableau currently indicates an infeasible basic solution, and if it indicates an infeasible feasible region.

\begin{array}{c|ccccc|c|l} &{{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & {{x4}} & {{x5}} & -1\\ \hline {{y1}} & {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{a15}} & {{b1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{y2}} & {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{a25}} & {{b2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{y3}} & {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} & {{a35}} & {{b3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ {{y4}} & {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}} & {{a45}} & {{b4}} & = -{{t4}}\\ {{y1}} & {{a51}} & {{a52}} & {{a53}} & {{a54}} & {{a55}} & {{b5}} & = -{{t5}}\\ \hline -1 & {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{c4}} & {{c5}} & {{d}} &=f\\ \hline & {{s1}} & {{s2}} & {{s3}} & {{s4}} & {{s5}} & =g & \end{array}

This tableau indicates that the basic dual solution is infeasible.

This tableau indicates the basic dual solution is feasible.

This tableau indicates that the dual problem is infeasible.

This tableau indicates that the dual problem has unbounded feasible region.

This tableau indicates that the dual problem has unbounded (below) objective function.

This tableau indicates the basic dual solution is optimal.

outcomes.title: Dual Simplex Algorithm
outcomes.description: Given a primal max problem, state the dual problem and use the simplex algorithm to solve it.
outcomes.template:
Suppose we wish to maximize f(x_1, x_2, x_3, x_4) = {{objectivefunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{row1}} & \leq & {{b1}} \\ {{row2}} & \leq & {{b2}} \\ {{row3}} & \leq & {{b3}} \\ {{row4}} & \leq & {{b4}} \\ x_1, x_2, x_3, x_4 & \geq & 0. \end{array}

State the dual problem, encode both problems in a tableau and use the simplex algorithm to find the optimal solution to the dual problem.

The dual problem is: minimize g(y_1, y_2, y_3, y_4) = {{dualfunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{drow1}} & \geq & {{c1}} \\ {{drow2}} & \geq & {{c2}} \\ {{drow3}} & \geq & {{c3}} \\ {{drow4}} & \geq & {{c4}} \\ y_1, y_2, y_3, y_4 & \geq & 0. \end{array}

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{r|cccc|c|l} & x_1 & x_2 & x_3 & x_4 & -1\\ \hline y_1 & {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{b1}} & = -t_1\\ y_2 & {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{b2}} & = -t_2\\ y_3 & {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} & {{b3}} & = -t_3\\ y_4 & {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}} & {{b4}} & = -t_4\\ \hline -1 & {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{c4}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline & s_1 & s_2 & s_3 & s_4 & =g \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{r|cccc|c|l} & {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & {{x4}} & -1\\ \hline {{y1}} & {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fa13}} & {{Fa14}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{y2}} & {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fa23}} & {{Fa24}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{y3}} & {{Fa31}} & {{Fa32}} & {{Fa33}} & {{Fa34}} & {{Fb3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ {{y4}} & {{Fa41}} & {{Fa42}} & {{Fa43}} & {{Fa44}} & {{Fb4}} & = -{{t4}}\\ \hline -1 & {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fc3}} & {{Fc4}} & {{Fd}}& =f\\ \hline & {{s1}} & {{s2}} & {{s3}} & {{s4}} & =g \end{array} with y_1 = {{y1value}}, y_2 = {{y2value}}, y_3 = {{y3value}}, and y_4 = {{y4value}}. The optimal dual objective value is g({{y1value}}, {{y2value}}, {{y3value}}, {{y4value}}) = {{optimalsolution}}

outcomes.title: Solving Dual Problems
outcomes.description:
Given a primal max problem, state the dual problem and use the simplex algorithm to either find the optimal solution,
or determine if the dual is infeasible or unbounded.
outcomes.template:
For each of the following linear optimization problems, state the dual problem. T hen use the simplex algorithm to determine if the dual linear optimization problem achieves optimality, or if the dual problem is infeasible or unbounded.

Maximize f(x_1, x_2, x_3) = {{objectivefunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{row1}} & \leq & {{b1}} \\ {{row2}} & \leq & {{b2}} \\ {{row3}} & \leq & {{b3}} \\ x_1, x_2, x_3 & \geq & 0. \end{array}

The dual problem is as follows: minimize g(y_1, y_2, y_3) = {{dualfunction}} subject to: \begin{array}{rcl} {{drow1}} & \geq & {{c1}} \\ {{drow2}} & \geq & {{c2}} \\ {{drow3}} & \geq & {{c3}} \\ y_1, y_2, y_3 & \geq & 0. \end{array}

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{r|ccc|c|l} & x_1 & x_2 & x_3 & -1\\ \hline y_1 & {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{b1}} & = -t_1\\ y_2 & {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{b2}} & = -t_2\\ y_3 & {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{b3}} & = -t_3\\ \hline -1 & {{c1}} & {{c2}} & {{c3}} & {{d}}& =f\\ \hline & s_1 & s_2 & s_3 & =g & \end{array}

The final tableau should be something like: \begin{array}{r|ccc|c|l} & {{x1}} & {{x2}} & {{x3}} & -1\\ \hline {{y1}} & {{Fa11}} & {{Fa12}} & {{Fa13}} & {{Fb1}} & = -{{t1}}\\ {{y2}} & {{Fa21}} & {{Fa22}} & {{Fa23}} & {{Fb2}} & = -{{t2}}\\ {{y3}} & {{Fa31}} & {{Fa32}} & {{Fa33}} & {{Fb3}} & = -{{t3}}\\ \hline -1 & {{Fc1}} & {{Fc2}} & {{Fc3}} &{{Fd}}& =f\\ \hline & {{s1}} & {{s2}} & {{s3}} & =g & \end{array}

The dual feasible region is empty. The optimal solution occurs when y_1 = {{y1value}}, y_2 = {{y2value}}, and y_3 = {{y3value}}. The optimal objective value is g({{y1value}}, {{y2value}}, {{y3value}}) = {{optimalsolution}}. The dual objective function is unbounded (below).

outcomes.title: Noncanonical Dual Problems

outcomes.template:

outcomes.title: Optimal Pure Strategies
outcomes.description: Find the optimal  strategy for both players for a zero sum game.
outcomes.template:
Suppose we had a zero sum game with payoff matrix: {{payoff}} Find the optimal mixed strategy for both players for this game. Then identify the vonNuemann value of the game and state which player is favored.

After domination the payoff matrix should look like: {{domination}} with row strategies {{r1strat}}, {{r2strat}} and {{r3strat}} remaining, and column strategies {{c1strat}}, {{c2strat}} and {{c3strat}} remaining.

Since {{optimalsolution}} is a saddle point corresponding to row strategy {{ropt}} and column strategy {{copt}}, these are the optimal strategies for both players. The vonNuemann value of the game is {{optimalsolution}}, so the game {{conclusion}}.

outcomes.title: Optimal Mixed Strategies

outcomes.template:
Suppose we had a zero sum game with payoff matrix: {{payoff}} Find the optimal mixed strategy for both players for this game. Then identify the vonNuemann value of the game and state which player is favored.

After domination the payoff matrix should look like: {{domination}} with row strategies {{r1strat}}, {{r2strat}} and {{r3strat}} remaining, and column strategies {{c1strat}}, {{c2strat}} and {{c3strat}} remaining.

outcomes.title: Determining Payoff Matrices
outcomes.description: Find the payoff matrix for a given game.
outcomes.template:
Rowan and Colleen are playing a card game together. Rowan is dealt a {{rn1}} of {{rsuit1}}, {{rn2}} of {{rsuit2}}, {{rn3}} of {{rsuit3}}, and a {{rn4}} of {{rsuit4}}. Colleen is dealt a {{cn1}} of {{csuit1}}, {{cn2}} of {{csuit2}}, {{cn3}} of {{csuit3}}, and a {{cn4}} of {{csuit4}}. Each player picks a card in secret and places it face down on the table, then they flip them over at the same time. If they suits are the same, Rowan wins points equal to the sum of the card values. Otherwise, Colleen wins points equal to the sum of the card values.

Write out the payoff matrix for this game.

\begin{array}{c|cccc|} & {{cn1}}{{cs1}} & {{cn2}}{{cs2}} & {{cn3}}{{cs3}} & {{cn4}}{{cs4}}\\ \hline {{rn1}}{{rs1}} & {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} \\ {{rn2}}{{rs2}} & {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} \\ {{rn3}}{{rs3}} & {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} \\ {{rn4}}{{rs4}} & {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}}\\ \hline \end{array}

Each player Rowan and Colleen selects a number from 1 through {{n}} and reveals them at the same time. If the difference between selections is less than {{m}}, the player with the larger number wins points equal to the sum of the selections. Otherwise the player with the smaller number wins points equal to the sum of the selections. If the selections are equal, neither player wins any points.

Write out the payoff matrix for this game.

\begin{array}{ r| {{#C}} {{c}} {{/C}} | } {{#col}} & {{col}} {{/col}} \\ \hline {{#data}} {{row}} {{#data2}} & {{entry}} {{/data2}} \\ {{/data}} \hline \end{array}

Colonel Rowan is attacking a town defended by Colonel Colleen. Rowan has {{Rtroop}} regiments and Colleen has {{Ctroop}}. There are two routes to the town. Rowan and select any number of regiments to attack along each route, up to a total of {{Rtroop}} and Colleen can likewise assign her {{Ctroop}} regiments along either route, neither knowing beforehand the other's strategy.

Along each route, whatever side has a greater number of regiments wins points equal to the number of regiments sent by the opposing side (as they capture those units). Furthermore, if Rowan wins along either route, he captures the town also worth one point.

If they are different but the sum is even, Rowan pays Collen dollars equal to the difference between selections. Otherwise the Colleen pays Rowan ${{n}}.

Write out the payoff matrix for this game.

\begin{array}{ r| {{#C}} {{c}} {{/C}} | } {{#col}} & {{col}} {{/col}} \\ \hline {{#data}} {{row}} {{#data2}} & {{entry}} {{/data2}} \\ {{/data}} \hline \end{array}

outcomes.title: Transportation Problem
outcomes.description: Given a transportation problem, find the shipping schedule which minimizes shipping cost.
outcomes.template:
Suppose we had four warehouses with {{W1}}, {{W2}}, {{W3}}, {{W4}} {{good}}s each, and four markets who require {{M1}}, {{M2}}, {{M3}}, {{M4}} {{good}}s each. The cost to ship from Warehouse i to Market j is encoded in the following matrix: {{A}}

Encode this problem in a transportation tableau and use the transportation algorithm to find the shipping schedule which minimizes cost.

The initial tableau should look like: \begin{array}{|cccc|c} \hline {{a11}} & {{a12}} & {{a13}} & {{a14}} & {{W1}} \\ {{a21}} & {{a22}} & {{a23}} & {{a24}} & {{W2}} \\ {{a31}} & {{a32}} & {{a33}} & {{a34}} & {{W3}} \\ {{a41}} & {{a42}} & {{a43}} & {{a44}} & {{W4}} \\ \hline {{M1}} & {{M2}} & {{M3}} & {{M4}} & {{total}} \end{array}

The minimal shipping cost may be achieved by shipping {{#data}} {{Q}} {{good}}s from Warehouse {{W}} to Market {{M}}, {{/data}} for total cost of ${{optimalsolution}} (note that while this cost is unique, the shipping quantities may not be).

outcomes.title: Transportation Modeling
outcomes.description: FIXME
outcomes.template:
A rental service needs to purchase {{good}}s to be rented for the next 4 days. The demand for {{good}}s for these days are {{M1}}, {{M2}}, {{M3}}, {{M4}} each. It costs {{newcost}} credits to purchase them new. It costs {{slowcost}} credits to fix them up for use again after a full day of work. This can be speed up for {{fastcost}} credits to be ready the very next day. How many new {{good}}s should be purchased, and how many after each day should be fast fixed or slow fixed to minimize cost?

{{purchase}} {{good}}s should be purchased new. After the first day, {{day1fast}} should be fast fixed, and {{day1slow}} should be slow fixed. After the second day, {{day2fast}} should be fast fixed, and {{day2slow}} should be slow fixed. After the third day, {{day3fast}} should be fast fixed. This results in a minimal cost of {{optimalsolution}} credits.

outcomes.title: Assignment Problem
outcomes.description: Given an assignment problem, find the assignment that minimizes cost.
outcomes.template:
Suppose we had five jobs to be done by five workers, each worker is to do exactly one job. The cost for job i to be done by worker j (in thousands of dollars) is encoded in the following matrix: {{A}}

Use the assignment algorithm to assign jobs to workers in a way that minimizes cost.

The minimal assignment cost may be achieved by assigning {{#data}} Job {{W}} to Worker {{M}}, {{/data}} for total cost of {{optimalsolution}} thousand dollars (note that while this cost is unique, the specific assignment may not be).
